.TH "URLPATTERN.PORT" "3JS" "August 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
URLPattern.port \- URLPattern: port property
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]port\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]URLPattern\f[R] interface is a string containing the pattern used
to match the port part of a URL.
.PP
This is the normalized value of the port pattern passed to the
constructor, or an inherited value from a \f[CR]baseURL\f[R] passed to
the constructor, or the default value (\f[CR]\(dq*\(dq\f[R]), which
matches any port.
.PP
Note that it may also be set implicitly to the empty string
(\f[CR]\(dq\(dq\f[R]) if the pattern is specified using an
\f[CR]url\f[R] or \f[CR]baseURL\f[R] string and the port is not
explicitly set.
This empty string matches against URLs that use the default port
(\f[CR]443\f[R]).
.SH VALUE
A string.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic usage
The following example creates a \f[CR]URLPattern\f[R] object with
\f[CR](80|443|8080)\f[R] for the \f[CR]port\f[R] part and logs the
property.
This pattern matches any URL that has the port \f[CR]80\f[R],
\f[CR]443\f[R], or \f[CR]8080\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] pattern = \f[B]new\f[R] URLPattern({ port: \(dq(80|443|8080)\(dq });
console.log(pattern.port); \f[I]// \(dq(80|443|8080)\(dq\f[R]
console.log(pattern.test(\(dqhttp://example.com:8080/\(dq)); \f[I]// true\f[R]
.EE
